C. Data Preprocessing

Missing Value Handling

Numerical features Median (robust to outliers) Categorical features Mode (most frequent value)

impute_mode <- function(x){
  ux <- na.omit(unique(x))
  if(length(ux) == 0) return(NA)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}

data_clean <- data
num_cols_all <- names(data_clean)[sapply(data_clean, is.numeric)]
for(col in num_cols_all){
  if(any(is.na(data_clean[[col]]))){
    data_clean[[col]][is.na(data_clean[[col]])] <- median(data_clean[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
  }
}

cat_cols_all <- names(data_clean)[sapply(data_clean, function(x) is.character(x) | is.factor(x))]
for(col in cat_cols_all){
  if(any(is.na(data_clean[[col]]))){
    data_clean[[col]][is.na(data_clean[[col]])] <- impute_mode(data_clean[[col]])
  }
}

Feature Engineering

Creating new feature: Study_Efficiency

if(all(c("Exam_Score","Hours_Studied") %in% names(data_clean))){
  data_clean <- data_clean %>%
    mutate(Study_Efficiency = ifelse(is.na(Hours_Studied) | Hours_Studied==0,
                                     NA, Exam_Score/Hours_Studied))
}

Outlier Handling (IQR Capping)

Outliers can heavily influence model performance. IQR-based capping reduces extreme values without removing data points.

num_cols_clean <- names(data_clean)[sapply(data_clean, is.numeric)]
for(col in num_cols_clean){
  Q1 <- quantile(data_clean[[col]], 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
  Q3 <- quantile(data_clean[[col]], 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
  IQR_val <- Q3 - Q1
  lb <- Q1 - 1.5 * IQR_val
  ub <- Q3 + 1.5 * IQR_val
  data_clean[[col]] <- ifelse(data_clean[[col]] < lb, lb,
                              ifelse(data_clean[[col]] > ub, ub, data_clean[[col]]))
}

Encode Categorical Variables

One-hot encoding converts categorical variables to numerical format.

cat_cols_to_encode <- names(data_clean)[sapply(data_clean, function(x) is.character(x) | is.factor(x))]
if(length(cat_cols_to_encode) > 0){
  data_encoded <- fastDummies::dummy_cols(data_clean,
                                          select_columns = cat_cols_to_encode,
                                          remove_first_dummy = TRUE,
                                          remove_selected_columns = TRUE)
} else {
  data_encoded <- data_clean
}

data_encoded <- data_encoded %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.factor), as.numeric)) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.logical), as.numeric))

Data Transformation and Scaling

Apply logarithmic or square root transformations to skewed features. Standardization ensures all predictors are on the same scale.

num_cols_encoded <- names(data_encoded)[sapply(data_encoded, is.numeric)]
for(col in num_cols_encoded){
  unique_vals <- unique(na.omit(data_encoded[[col]]))
  if(length(unique_vals) <= 2) next
  sk <- e1071::skewness(data_encoded[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
  if(!is.na(sk) && sk > 1){
    data_encoded[[paste0(col,"_log")]] <- log1p(pmax(0, data_encoded[[col]]))
  } else if(!is.na(sk) && sk > 0.5){
    data_encoded[[paste0(col,"_sqrt")]] <- sqrt(pmax(0, data_encoded[[col]]))
  }
}

final_numeric_cols <- names(data_encoded)[sapply(data_encoded, is.numeric)]
scale_cols <- setdiff(final_numeric_cols, "Exam_Score")
if(length(scale_cols) > 0) data_encoded[scale_cols] <- scale(data_encoded[scale_cols])

data_final_for_fs <- data_encoded

Mutual Information Feature Selection

Mutual information selects features with (possibly non-linear) association with the target.

mi_scores<-FSelectorRcpp::information_gain(Exam_Score ~ ., data = data_final_for_fs[, c(numeric_cols, "Exam_Score")])
## Warning in .information_gain.data.frame(x = x, y = y, type = type, equal =
## equal, : Dependent variable is a numeric! It will be converted to factor with
## simple factor(y). We do not discretize dependent variable in FSelectorRcpp by
## default! You can choose equal frequency binning discretization by setting equal
## argument to TRUE.
mi_selected<-mi_scores$attributes[mi_scores$importance>0]
cat("Features selected by mutual information (Exam_Score):\n")

Binary Classification

Convert to binary classification problem: High Performance (Yes/No)

data_bin <- cls_data
if(!"High_Performance" %in% names(data_bin)){
  data_bin$High_Performance <- ifelse(data_bin$Exam_Score >= 70, "Yes", "No")
  data_bin$High_Performance <- as.factor(data_bin$High_Performance)
}

set.seed(123)
trainIndex2 <- caret::createDataPartition(data_bin$High_Performance, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
trainData2 <- data_bin[trainIndex2, ]
testData2  <- data_bin[-trainIndex2, ]

Logistic Regression Model 

log_preds <- intersect(c("Hours_Studied", "Attendance", "Previous_Scores"), names(data_bin))
if(length(log_preds) == 0){
  cat("No predictors found for logistic regression. Skipping logistic model.\n")
} else {
  fmla_log <- as.formula(paste("High_Performance ~", paste(log_preds, collapse = " + ")))
  model_log <- glm(fmla_log, data = trainData2, family = binomial)
  cat("Logistic Regression Summary:\n")
  print(summary(model_log))
  
  prob <- predict(model_log, newdata = testData2, type = "response")
  pred_log <- ifelse(prob > 0.5, "Yes", "No")
  pred_log <- factor(pred_log, levels = c("No", "Yes"))
  conf_mat_log <- confusionMatrix(pred_log, testData2$High_Performance)
  cat("\nConfusion Matrix for Logistic Regression:\n")
  print(conf_mat_log)
  
  cat("\n=== Logistic Regression (High_Performance) Metrics ===\n")
  cat("Accuracy:", round(conf_mat_log$overall["Accuracy"], 4), "\n")
  cat("Precision (Yes):", round(conf_mat_log$byClass["Pos Pred Value"], 4), "\n")
  cat("Recall (Yes)   :", round(conf_mat_log$byClass["Sensitivity"], 4), "\n")
  cat("F1-Score (Yes) :", round(conf_mat_log$byClass["F1"], 4), "\n")
}
